segments.text: With Dr. Greenhut, I remember his chuckling later that Mr. Rutter gave him a long lecture about not bringing in a bunch of conservatives.
The Department of Economics that I knew when I first got here was very high in quality of its instruction here.
They were really good at the undergraduate and master's level, but then here came this group of senior scholars.
The funding for that was from normal A&M sources.
They were not a big gift.
Was there any federal money that you recall that made that possible?
It was a mixed bag, actually, Haskell.
The primary source, of course, was state funding, you know, from the normal sources.
But we did have some development grants and outside money and things like that, and federal money, too.
You mentioned Tiger Teague's contributions.
He got us everything that he could from the federal government, including his board of faculty.
students and so forth.
Not only just buildings.
I mentioned only buildings, but that's only a part of what he got for us.
Did he have any pet, any programs that were of
highest priority to him?
You mean Tiger?
Yes, sir.
Oh, yeah.
I'm glad to see that the building recognizes his real, he was really gung-ho on space, NASA.
Ah, yes, yes, yes.
Yes, that's right.
He and LBGA got the center down at Houston.
It was probably primarily responsible.
But he got us all that money for the space building.
It's called the Tiger T. Well, you know, I don't have to tell you that.
In the 70s, my office was there a good bit because the president's office was then across the street.
Now, that causes my mind to jump back to organization.
When Dr. Harrington retired,
Mr. Rutter became president of the system and of the university.
Well, officially, Dr. Harrington didn't retire.
He became director of foreign programs.
And at that time, when that happened, yes, the board brought it about.
Mr. Rutter was appointed to both positions, same as Dr. Harrington had held at one time.
And so when you went to him for a decision,
you knew that it did not need to go beyond his desk.
Did it make the institution function more efficiently?
I think so, because he and I were on the same wavelength and team.
He moved down to the system building, to the chancellor's office, and left me in the Koch building.
Literally, without portfolio, I was running A&M.
at that time.
Of course, he was coordinating the whole thing.
But we would meet when he was in town weekly down in the system building for at least an hour and a half every week.
And I would have the things I wanted him to bless and discuss with him.
And he would usually endorse them, most of them.
Your title did not change.
Oh, no.
I was still Vice President for Academic Affairs and Dean of the Graduate School.
Mr. Rutter wasn't a great believer in high-sounding titles.
But in fact, you were the...
I was the president of A&M in operation, right.
I don't want to make that claim.
No, I hear you.
The enrollment was going up every year.
The boom was coming.
Initially we built up graduate enrollment more than we did undergraduate, but eventually undergraduate enrollment took over.
And now, of course, it's in the ascendancy.
Did any of the programs move faster than you expected them to?
I was surprised.
I don't know if it was faster than I expected, but because of the tactics we were using in chemistry as well as economics that you mentioned, we brought in groups of people at once.
In other words, established an instant department on the rise.
Mostly these were senior research scholars.
We weren't looking for outstanding teachers.
Many of them were excellent teachers too.
Now I'm assuming that didn't do it in other departments simply because the resources.
That was it mostly.
Later I convinced Mr.
Rudder if we were going to ever be a great university we had to have a strong level of arts too and that's when we started to build it up and now it's well recognized.
Doing quite well.
Let's see.
Do you remember any good Aggie story, anecdotes that may have nothing to do with what we've been talking about, just their good recollections of?
Well, Haskell, I'm not an Aggie, you know, by graduation, only affiliation.
Neither am I.
But I used to, the Aggie stories that were told me, I would promptly forget because I hated most of them.
No, there's a lot of them, but I can't think of any right now.
But particularly the ones that they would try to
Make A&M out as it dunks or something like that.
No, but do you remember any attempted pranks at Mr. Rutter or anybody else that may not have gone off?
No, I'm sure there were some, and I probably knew some at one time.
Let me share one on Hannigan.
The, he was deeply concerned about the civilian students walking across the drill field.
Oh, yeah.
And they were wearing a path.
So he gave direction to somebody that they strung some slick wire all the way around the drill field, around the trees.
And the first night, the wire was cut, of course, into a zillion pieces.
We had a committee meeting the next day, and he couldn't figure out where anybody could have gotten all those wire cutters.
And I said, well, I suspect they got the pliers out of their pickup trucks.
And he said something to the effect, what, they carry pliers with them in their truck?
And I told him, yes, for a farm boy or a ranch boy that was a normal
And he was kind of taken aback by that.
Oh, it was Hannigan.
Yes, sir.
Oh, yeah, Rudder would have known.
Oh, yeah, Mr.
Rudder would have known.
No, Rudder wasn't in the room.
No, I know that.
No, Hannigan was taken aback.
All right, let's see.
Getting further along, for you personally, of what are you most proud during your A&M experience?
The academic programs in general and the faculty, the initial faculty that we brought in that really transformed A&M from a college, teaching college, to a model university.
Without identifying names, but you know the names as well as I do that were here.
Is there anything?
Really the graduates, building up with the graduate programs was probably my strongest thing that I prized most.
A lot of people would probably put that secondary, but I wouldn't because research and top teaching has always been my priority, and I think they go hand in hand.
In the run of events during your years at A&M, which events did you enjoy most?
Oh, seeing the aspirations and the dreams develop, I guess, without singling out individual ones.
There's dozens of those.
What about, did you like commencements?
No, frankly, I'm not a crate, because as you and I both know, you've heard one in commencement speech, you've heard them all, or most.
Occasionally there's one that stimulates you and it's different, but most of them are fairly rote and routine.
No, I never cared too much for the protocol or the formality of academia.
I've decided that one, in being away for 17 years and coming back, one of the important ingredients to A&M's experience are a number of events that are inclusive.
fish camp, midnight yell practice, muster, elephant walk, commencement where every name is called, every hand is shaken, everybody gets their moment in the spotlight.
That those, doesn't matter whether you're male or female, whether you're rural or urban, Texas born or anywhere else, there is that moment.
And many, many institutions have dropped the commencement and now have a kind of a quick hereby confer upon you to be seated.
And it takes a long time here now with three commencements in the spring and two in the winter, but I think that's a good investment.
I think that's a tradition that's paid off.
But to respond to your
query about the student activities and the traditions that have developed, all of which I honor and respect.
I was never deep into the student activities when I was at A&M.
Oh, I had students, sure.
I had graduate students.
I had a lot of undergraduates that I still remember fondly, but I never got involved emotionally into the thing that really kicks me off.
Just going to the football stage with you to hear the Aggie war half.
Okay, two more questions.
Let's make believe that somebody gave you a million dollar check that had the stipulation you must give it to Texas A&M, but you can decide the use of the benefit of that.
What would you give it for?
I would first do current research to find out what's going on in certain activities that I have a particular fondness for.
And if I felt there was sufficient evidence, then I would concentrate on these areas, building up faculty, students, and programs to the utmost in these areas.
Some of the other lasting values that most of the former students think about after years of being gone from here, I went indoors too, some of these traditions.
At the time that I was there, I wasn't gung-ho about them, to be frank, but now I am.
I think they have value.
Last question.
What did it mean to you, as you look back, what has it meant to you that you came to Texas A&M back there in 1957?
No, no, no, no.
It was in 48.
48, yes, yes.
What did it mean to you that you came here?
At that time or now?
Now.
Now, seeing what's developed
on the shores of the Brazos River over here.
No, just like Earl Rudder, I'm sure, from above, he would be proud of what happened at A&M and what's developed.
And I'm glad that I had a part in it.
I'm not an Aggie, you will know.
Well, I tell people there are some of us that are Aggies by choice.
Yeah, that's what it is.
We could have been other places, and we chose here.
And I want to thank you for what you meant
because I don't believe this institution today would be what it is if you hadn't been here.
Well, thank you.
